# Wallet Auth

Privy and wagmi are wired in `src/components/app-providers.tsx`: `PrivyProvider` (embedded wallets) wraps `TRPCReactProvider` and `@privy-io/wagmi`'s `WagmiProvider`. Chains and transports live in `src/lib/wagmi.ts`. The `Header` (`src/components/header.tsx`) drives login/logout via `usePrivy` and reads the connected address via wagmi's `useAccount`.

## Session
Privy stores the session in a `privy-token` cookie. There is no server session store; the cookie is the source of truth.

## Route protection
Two layers, both keyed on the `privy-token` cookie:
- `src/proxy.ts` — edge proxy. `PUBLIC_ROUTES` lists routes reachable while logged out; everything else redirects to `/`, and authenticated users on a public route bounce to `/protected`.
- `src/app/protected/layout.tsx` — server layout that re-checks the cookie and redirects to `/` if missing.

## Server-side verification
`src/trpc/init.ts` reads the token from the request cookie, calls Privy's `verifyAuthToken`, and puts `privyUserId` on the tRPC context. `protectedProcedure` throws `UNAUTHORIZED` when it is null. Trust `privyUserId`, not client-supplied identity.

## Add a protected page
Create the route under `src/app/protected/`; the layout guards it. Add `/your-path` to `PUBLIC_ROUTES` in `src/proxy.ts` only if it must be public.
